{"timestamp": "2025-12-05 18:19:38.483184", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Thanks — I've submitted the solution.\n\nSummary of what I submitted\n- is_anomaly: true\n- faulty_devices (localized): server_access_router; core/distribution routers; load_balancer (10.200.0.7); web_server_0..3 (10.200.0.3–.6)\n- root_cause_name chosen: [\"ospf_area_misconfiguration\", \"load_balancer_overload\"]\n\nNotes and caveats\n- The diagnosis report localizes the primary policy/segmentation issue to the server_access_router and upstream core/distribution routers because 10.200.0.0/24 is directly connected and advertised via OSPF with no filtering; I selected ospf_area_misconfiguration to represent the routing/advertisement-based cause of the exposure. If you prefer a different root-cause label from the available list (e.g., ospf_neighbor_missing or ospf_acl_block), I can resubmit.\n- For the HTTP status 000 anomaly, the report points to application-layer behavior (web servers or load balancer sending non-standard HTTP responses). I selected load_balancer_overload as the root-cause label from the provided list to reflect a plausible load-balancer/proxy-related problem; however, the evidence more strongly suggests an application/proxy misconfiguration (HTTP/0.9 or header omission) rather than classic overload. If you want the root cause relabeled to better match an application misconfiguration, tell me which available label you'd prefer and I will update the submission.\n\nNext recommended actions (concise)\n- Network segmentation: add/enable ACLs or firewall rules on server_access_router or an inline firewall to prevent host subnets from reaching backend server IPs; alternatively, avoid advertising 10.200.0.0/24 into OSPF or advertise only the load balancer IP via a handled VIP.\n- HTTP troubleshooting: capture tcpdump on load balancer and a web server during a request to inspect whether an HTTP status line is sent; check web server and load balancer configs/logs for HTTP/0.9 mode or connection handling that may omit headers.\n- Collect the FRR configs, ACLs, and packet captures I listed earlier if you want a follow-up with concrete config changes.\n\nIf you want me to resubmit with different root_cause_name values or remove/add faulty devices, tell me which labels from the available list to use and I will update the submission.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 3006, "output_tokens": 499, "total_tokens": 3505, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 2688}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 0}}}
